As we have seen, although criticisms have been levelled against Livy as a historical authority, the majority of readers have found the style in which he has told his story interesting and delightful. His view of what he should aim at would naturally compel him to do this within the limits of his powers. His earlier rhetorical training gave him a greater command of the language, but resulted in what at first seems to a modern a strange habit of constructing speeches which are put without

· documentary authority in the mouths of prominent characters.

Even this practice, however, will be found to prove of material service for the vivid representation of these characters and of the situations in which they are placed.
